  <h1>Bill Thurston on Reading Hard Things</h1>
  <time datetime=2013-12-25T04:30:49Z class="post-date">Wed, Dec 25, 2013</time>
  <blockquote>
<p>I was really amazed by my first encounters with serious mathematics textbooks. I was very interested and impressed by the quality of the reasoning, but it was quite hard to stay alert and focused. After a few experiences of reading a few pages only to discover that I really had no idea what I&#8217;d just read, I learned to drink lots of coffee, slow way down, and accept that I needed to read these books at 1/10th or 1/50th standard reading speed, pay attention to every single word and backtrack to look up all the obscure numbers of equations and theorems in order to follow the arguments.</p>

<p><span id="quote-attribute">—Bill Thurston, from the foreword to <em><a href="http://matrixeditions.com/Thurstonforeword.html">Teichmüller Theory and Applications to Geometry, Topology, and Dynamics</a></em></span></p>
</blockquote>

<p>He goes on to talk about the importance of using one&#8217;s whole mind in understanding mathematics. You might want to <a href="http://matrixeditions.com/Thurstonforeword.html">check it out</a>.</p>

